Financial metrics temporarily unavailable (rate limited) - 2025-09-23

Title   : Schneider Electric extends ISRO partnership for space mission operations
Source  : www.thehindubusinessline.com
Published: 2025-09-23T12:48:46
Fetched : 2025-09-23T17:06:05.132684
URL     : https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/schneider-electric-extends-isro-partnership-for-space-mission-operations/article70084516.ece
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Schneider Electric has announced its continued partnership with the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) to support India’s space missions through advanced automation technology at the Satish Dhawan Space Centre in Sriharikota.
The French industrial technology company has been providing automation systems for ISRO’s launch vehicle and satellite operations for the past 15 years. The partnership has contributed to several landmark missions including Chandrayaan-3, GSLV-F16, and other critical space endeavors.
Schneider Electric has deployed multiple automation systems across various applications at SDSC SHAR, positioning itself as a key technology partner for India’s space programme. The company’s solutions support the seamless operations of ISRO’s launch and satellite missions.
Space journey
“India’s space journey is a symbol of innovation, resilience, and global leadership, and we at Schneider Electric are honoured to be part of this remarkable mission,” said Deepak Sharma, Zone President for Greater India and MD & CEO of Schneider Electric India.
ISRO has achieved significant milestones in recent years, including the Mars Orbiter Mission and Chandrayaan lunar expeditions, establishing India as a major player in global space exploration. The organization continues to expand its satellite launch portfolio while pursuing ambitious interplanetary missions.
The partnership reinforces Schneider Electric’s commitment to supporting mission-critical infrastructure in India’s expanding space sector, as the country accelerates its space exploration ambitions.
Published on September 23, 2025

