Funds raised through the fresh issue will be allocated toward debt repayment, establishing a new roasted gram flour and gram flour production facility in Darjeeling, and general corporate purposes. The OFS portion will facilitate a stake reduction by promoters—from 75.3% to 64.1%.
Issue structure and anchor investment
The total issue size is Rs 409 crore, including a fresh issue of Rs 130 crore and an offer-for-sale (OFS) of Rs 278.8 crore. Notably, Bengal Finance, backed by investor Ashish Kacholia, participated as an anchor investor ahead of the IPO launch.
About Ganesh Consumer Products
Headquartered in Kolkata, Ganesh Consumer Products is the third-largest packaged wheat flour brand in East India by value. It holds a strong presence in wheat-based products like maida, sooji, and dalia. The company is also a top two player in gram-based products—sattu and besan—commanding market shares of 43% and 5%, respectively.
Its flagship “Ganesh” brand features 42 products across 232 SKUs, including atta, maida, sooji, dalia, sattu, besan, spices, instant mixes, and ethnic snacks. The B2C segment drives nearly 77% of revenue, supported by a wide distribution network comprising 28 C&F agents, 9 super stockists, and 972 distributors. Ganesh Consumer Products currently reaches over 70,000 retail outlets across West Bengal, Bihar, Odisha, Jharkhand, and Assam.
Financial performance of Ganesh Consumer Products
For FY25, the company reported a 12% YoY growth in revenue, reaching Rs 8,505 million. Profit after tax rose to Rs 35.4 crore, with an EBITDA margin of 8.6% and a PAT margin of 4.2%. Earnings per share (EPS) improved to Rs 8.8 from Rs 6.7 in the previous fiscal. At the upper price band, the IPO implies a valuation of 36.7x FY25 earnings, with a post-issue market capitalisation of Rs 1,301 crore.
What are analysts saying?
Anand Rathi Research has assigned a “Subscribe – Long Term” rating to the Ganesh Consumer Products IPO, citing the company’s leadership in regional markets, strong brand portfolio, and robust distribution network. While the IPO appears fully valued, its expansion into snacks and spices, combined with established brand equity, offers potential for long-term investors seeking exposure in the consumer staples segment.
