Title   : Pvt defence firms poised for 16–18% revenue growth in FY26: CRISIL 
Source  : www.thehindubusinessline.com
Published: 2025-09-23T14:09:29
Fetched : 2025-09-23T17:27:14.532222
URL     : https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/pvt-defence-firms-poised-for-1618-revenue-growth-in-fy26-crisil/article70085109.ece
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
India’s private defence sector is expected to post 16–18 per cent revenue growth in the current fiscal (FY26), driven by strong domestic demand, increased government policy support, and robust capital investments, according to CRISIL Ratings.
This projection follows an impressive 20 per cent compound annual growth rate (CAGR) achieved by private defence firms between FY22 and FY25. The sustained growth trajectory reflects the success of policy measures promoting indigenous defence production and self-reliance, which have drawn significant private investments into the sector.
An analysis of over 25 private defence companies rated by CRISIL Ratings, which together account for nearly half of the industry’s revenues, forms the basis for this outlook.
“Over the past three fiscals, defence companies have seen equity infusions of around ₹3,600 crore on a net worth base of ₹4,760 crore at the end of FY22,” said Jayashree Nandakumar, Director, CRISIL Ratings.
“While a third of this funding was used for working capital, nearly half went into capital expenditure, R&D, and innovation, helping private sector players scale capabilities and win larger orders.”
India’s private defence sector, though traditionally overshadowed by public sector undertakings, is rapidly gaining ground. This is being fuelled by government-led initiatives such as the Emergency Procurement plan, Atmanirbhar Bharat, Defence Acquisition Policy, and the defence production and export promotion strategy.
These initiatives are translating into a healthy pipeline of defence contracts. CRISIL estimates that the sector’s order book will expand to ₹55,000 crore by the end of FY26, up from ₹40,000 crore in FY25.
Key growth areas include, electronic warfare systems, C4 (Command, Control, Communications, Computers & Intelligence) systems, and aerospace equipment and components.
Published on September 23, 2025

