Title   : Silver’s maiden half-century: White metal's 50% annual returns is first ever and 2025 isn’t over yet 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-23T12:06:39
Fetched : 2025-09-23T18:04:44.904874
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/commodities/silvers-maiden-half-century-white-metal-50-annual-returns-is-first-ever-and-2025-isnt-over-yet/articleshow/124070653.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Silver's staggering rise is on the back of safe haven demand for bullion (gold and silver), industrial demand, festive boost and rupee weakness.
Here's how silver has performed over the past 10 years:
Over the past 10 years, silver has delivered double-digit returns on 6 occasions viz. 2016 (17%), 2019 (20%), 2020, 2022 (11%), 2024 (17%) and 2025. Silver's next best run came in 2020, a Covid year, when it delivered 46% annual returns as investors fell for bullion's safe haven appeal. In that year, gold rallied over 28%.On Tuesday, silver prices hit yet another lifetime high of Rs 1,34,990 on the MCX. Around 3:10 pm, the December contracts were trading at Rs 1,34,840, gaining Rs 1,285 or 1%.
Silver price outlook 2025
Anuj Gupta, Director at Ya Wealth Global Research said that the strong sentiments around silver are likely to continue through 2025 on multiple levers which include the domestic festive season that began with the start of Navratri, rupee weakness and industrial demand for the white metal.Gupta expects silver to breach levels between Rs 1,40,000 and Rs 1,45,000 by the end of this year.
Renisha Chainani, Head – Research at Augmont sees a positive outlook for silver CY25, estimating a target of Rs 1,45,000 - Rs 1,50,000 per kg. In her view, several positive industrial factors underpin demand including solar, EV batteries, and electronics production.
This reflects a further 12% upside over the Monday closing price of Rs 1,33,555 per kg.
“Silver's dual status as both a precious and industrial metal gives it an edge. Prices are likely to be volatile but any uptick in global manufacturing and clean energy funding could move silver into the $48-50/oz world market range and Rs 1,45,000-1,50,000/kg locally,” she said.
Gold vs silver
On silver’s comparison with gold, Chainani said that the yellow metal will always play a role as a risk-off asset though silver will carry better beta exposure. She said that silver could see more extreme movements with higher upside potential due to higher industrial demand.“The outperformance of silver against gold will be dictated by the recovery in the industrial economy. Gold has exhibited as a stronger performer due to central bank buying and safe haven flows,” the Augmont analyst highlighted.
“The outperformance of silver against gold will be dictated by the recovery in the industrial economy. Gold has exhibited as a stronger performer due to central bank buying and safe haven flows,” the Augmont analyst highlighted.
Where silver scores is the valuation front, being deemed cheaper compared to gold.
“We believe silver is undervalued. The gold-silver ratio sits at 85, which is well above historic averages. Should industrial demand start to recover, silver can generate better percentage returns in FY25 than gold,” this analyst said.
Gold remains the best option on the stability front compared to its fairer peer.
The Augmont analyst said that silver’s outperformance will be patchy while gold’s returns will be consistent.
Gupta echoed a similar sentiment, opining that silver will likely remain ahead of gold this year.
3 triggers for silver
- Industrial activity arising from solar and electric vehicles
- Weaker U.S. dollar due to Fed rate cuts
- A spillover effect from gold's strength.
