Title   : Jefferies hikes Patanjali Foods’ target price to Rs 695. Here’s what the brokerage expects 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-23T09:44:48
Fetched : 2025-09-23T18:19:43.152103
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/jefferies-hikes-patanjali-foods-target-price-to-rs-695-heres-what-the-brokerage-expects/articleshow/124067461.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
It noted that the weak first quarter was largely due to the government’s customs duty cut on crude edible oil, which caused trade de-stocking and inventory valuation adjustments. With that now behind, Jefferies expects improved performance in the coming quarters, driven by volume growth and higher EBITDA margins.
“The upcoming festive season should help drive consumption,” the report said, though it added that the edible oil business is likely to see only low single-digit volume growth over the medium term.
The brokerage highlighted that Patanjali’s foods business – which includes ghee, biscuits, soya chunks, ayurvedic supplements, and staples – has faced headwinds. Management expects a gradual recovery through FY26, aiming for a stronger year-end performance.
Jefferies noted the company continues to guide for 10% topline growth and 8–10% margins in the foods segment. In the home and personal care segment, integrated post-acquisition in November 2024, management expects 15% CAGR growth and potential margin improvement of about 200 bps in the medium term.
On the palm plantation business, acreage has expanded from 60,000 hectares in March 2022 to over 92,000 hectares, with a steady ramp-up expected as plantations mature, supporting mid-to-high teens EBITDA margins.
Recent GST cuts across key categories such as ghee, biscuits, toothpaste, ayurvedic supplements, soya chunks, soaps, and face wash are expected to drive demand and volume growth, though near-term performance could see some de-stocking, the report added.
Jefferies outlined three scenarios for the stock:
- Base case: ~9% revenue CAGR over FY25-28E with 90 bps margin expansion; EPS growing at 19% CAGR, implying a price target of Rs 695 using SoTP methodology (38x Sep-27 EPS).
- Upside case: ~10% revenue CAGR with 130 bps margin expansion and 22% EPS CAGR, targeting Rs 760.
- Downside case: 5% revenue CAGR and 7% EPS CAGR, valuing the stock at Rs 480.
Around 1:30 pm today, Patanjali Foods shares were trading flat at Rs 598.80 on BSE.
